Using the num_col, numerical data are critic score, total sales, na sales, jp sales, pal sales, and other sales.

Examine Skewness:
First step is to see if the data is skewed in a specific direction. Depending how the data is skewed, transformations can be applied.

sapply(data[num_col], skewness, na.rm = TRUE)
## critic_score  total_sales     na_sales     jp_sales    pal_sales  other_sales 
##   -0.9104323    8.7746376    6.8975541    4.4894047    9.5857883    9.7935792
The following is how the data is skewed. critic score was -0.91 which is consider to be moderately left skewed. Since it is not skewed as much compared to the other variables, no transformation is applied. Total sales was extremely right-skewed, it was 8.77, log transformation will be used. The remaining of the data is also consider to have a strong or extreme right-skew, therefore, the remaining will also go through a Log transformation.

Fix Skew:
Based on the skew results (seen in Examine Skew) skewness will be fixed in total_sales, na_sales, jp_sales, pal_sales, and other_sales. Log transformation will be used to reduce the strong right skew. These variables show a strong positive skew. Critic score shows a moderate negative skew, this transformation was not done for this variable. Original data was used to fix skew.

skew_data <- data

sales_cols <- c("total_sales", "na_sales", "jp_sales", "pal_sales", "other_sales")

skew_data[sales_cols] <- lapply(skew_data[sales_cols], 
function(x) log10(x+1)
)

