This confirms that the scaling process was successful and that the variables are in the same scale.

Normalize columns:
Since variables have been scaled and skewness fixed, scaled data is going to be used to perform normalization.

Critic score normalization:
Critic score is between 0-10, using Min_Max it will convert the values between 0-1. The lowest score would be zero, highest score 1, everything else will be in between.

normalized_data <- scaled_data

normalized_data$critic_score <- (scaled_data$critic_score - min(scaled_data$critic_score, na.rm = TRUE)) / (max(scaled_data$critic_score, na.rm = TRUE) - min(scaled_data$critic_score, na.rm = TRUE))
Total Sales:
Decimal scaling was used to reduce the magnitude. Values will be between -1 and 1.

normalized_data$total_sales <- scaled_data$total_sales / 10^ceiling(log10(max(abs(scaled_data$total_sales), na.rm = TRUE)))
na_sales:
Max-abs is used to divide each value by the largest value in the column. There is a consistent range based on the maximum value. This also keeps the values between zero and one.

max(scaled_data$na_sales, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 8.9383
normalized_data$na_sales <- scaled_data$na_sales / max(abs(scaled_data$na_sales), na.rm = TRUE)
jp_sales:
Mean normalization is applied to center of the data and scaled by the range. Shows if the values are below or above the average. Since jp_sales has a skew of 4.49, it is not symmetric but there are also no extreme values.

normalized_data$jp_sales <- (scaled_data$jp_sales - mean(scaled_data$jp_sales, na.rm = TRUE)) / (max(scaled_data$jp_sales, na.rm = TRUE) - min(scaled_data$jp_sales, na.rm = TRUE))
pal_sales:
Min_max was also used for pal sales. Rescales the pal_sale value to 0-1. The values are still proportional to the original data, but larger numbers are not dominating the distribution.

normalized_data$pal_sales <- (scaled_data$pal_sales - min(scaled_data$pal_sales, na.rm = TRUE)) / (max(scaled_data$pal_sales, na.rm = TRUE) - min(scaled_data$pal_sales, na.rm = TRUE))
Other Sales:
Min-max was used to rescale value to 0-1. Even after the transformation, the data was still skewed, this puts the values on a common scale while keeping their order.

normalized_data$other_sales <- (scaled_data$other_sales - min(scaled_data$other_sales, na.rm = TRUE)) / (max(scaled_data$other_sales, na.rm = TRUE) - min(scaled_data$other_sales, na.rm = TRUE))
